{"cursor":"49768","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n\n, the first Jain tirthankara]] 'Jainism' (pronounced ), traditionally known as\nJaina dharma, is an Indian religion that prescribes a path of non-violence\ntowards all living beings. It is one of the oldest religions of the world\nfinding its roots in ancient India. Tradition says\nthat this belief has been preached by a succession of twenty-four propagators of\nfaith known as [[tirthankara]]. Jainism emphasises spiritual independence and\nequality between all forms of life. Practitioners of this religion believe that\nnon-violence and self-control is the means by which they can obtain liberation\nfrom the cycle of reincarnations.\n\nJainism is a religious minority in India, with 4.2 million followers, and has\nadherents in immigrant communities in Belgium, the United States, Hong Kong,\nJapan and Singapore. Jains have the highest degree of literacy for a\nreligious community in India, }} and their manuscript\nlibraries are the oldest in the country.\n","linknr":1316,"url":"Jainism","recorded":1362505822,"links":149,"instances":["day","month","grammar","jainism","philosophy","philosophy","jainism","india"],"pdf":["http://www.orissa.gov.in/e-magazine/Orissareview/2009/July/engpdf/62-64.pdf","http://www.orissa.gov.in/e-magazine/Orissareview/2009/July/engpdf/62-64.pdf"],"categories":["Jainism|","Indian religions","Religious identity","Religions that require vegetarianism","Transtheism","Nontheism"],"headings":["Core principles","Doctrines","Prominent figures","History","Community","Literature","Art and architecture","Customs and practices","See also","Notes","References"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8c/Jain_Prateek_Chihna.svg/90px-Jain_Prateek_Chihna.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4b/In-jain.svg/16px-In-jain.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b6/WLA_lacma_Jina_Rishabhanatha.jpg/220px-WLA_lacma_Jina_Rishabhanatha.j